The polite-then-forceful escalation.

There is a standard, well-mannered pattern for shutting down a misbehaving process, and it is worth doing in order rather than reaching straight for brute force. First, send sig-term, the polite request. Second, wait a few seconds, giving the process a real chance to clean up after itself: to flush its logs, close its database connections, and save its state. Third, only if it is still alive after that grace period, send sig-kill to force it down.

There is a neat trick for checking whether a process is still alive between those steps. Sending signal zero does not actually deliver anything to the process; it is a test-only signal that simply succeeds if the process exists and fails if it does not. So you can use it to decide whether the forceful kill is even necessary.

The mistake to avoid is reaching for sig-kill, the dash-nine signal, first. It is a very common new-user habit, and it is harmful, because sig-kill gives the process no chance to clean up. Files can be left half-written, databases corrupted, locks still held, temporary files orphaned. Always try the polite signal first, give it a few seconds, and escalate only if you must. This, by the way, is exactly what the service manager does for you behind the scenes when you stop a service: it sends sig-term, waits for a configured timeout, and only then sends sig-kill. You rarely have to perform the escalation by hand, but you should understand what is happening when you do.
